<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 93 / EBRD committee proposes sweeping inquiry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID HELLIER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE COMMITTEE which will look into allegations of overspending at the
European Bank of Reconstruction and Development wants a sweeping inquiry
which would examine most aspects of the bank's spending policies, including
'special flight arrangements'.
The audit committee, which includes EBRD directors, has recommended that
four firms of auditors be asked to tender for the role of adviser. The
bank's own external auditors, Deloitte Touche and Tohmatsu, would not be
among them.
The proposed terms of reference, which were put to a meeting of the EBRD's
board of directors yesterday, are rigorous. They include suggesting that
there should be what is described as an 'arms length' relationship with the
bank's management during the inquiry, given the sensitivity of the
committee's work. This, says the document setting out the proposals,
requires 'strict adherence to confidentiality and independence'.
Mr Claes de Neergaard, chairman of the audit committee, has said that, in
addition to external auditors, outside quantity surveyors and architects
should be appointed 'to ensure the appearance of absolute independence and
objectivity'.
The committee, which was charged by EBRD directors on April 19 with carrying
out the inquiry, has asked for between Pounds 200,000 and Pounds 300,000 for
the task. It plans to deliver its report by July 15 although there is scope
for it to take longer.
The bank yesterday declined to comment on the audit committee's proposals.
However Mr Jacques Attali, the bank's founder and president, is understood
to have told the board that the audit committee will get all the support it
needs.
Mr Attali is also believed to have accepted that the committee should look
at the bank's use of private jets. The inquiry was set up after widespread
calls from the bank's international shareholders following revelations in
the Financial Times of expenditure of Pounds 55.5m by the bank on its London
headquarters.
The committee's remit on expenses at the EBRD's headquarters will include,
but not be limited to, a review of:
The adequacy of the procedures for tendering and procurement to ensure that
services and goods were processed and payments were made in a regular and
proper fashion so as to obtain proper value for money.
The cost effectiveness of the specification for the project. The adequacy of
the arrangements for reporting progress on the project to the directors.
The adequacy of the arrangements for managing the project, within the bank
and between the main contracting parties, taking account of best practice in
the European Community.
The bank's policy and procedures with respect to fitting out the temporary
headquarters at Leadenhall Street.
</TEXT>
