<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 93 / Credit figures add to signs of recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BRITISH consumer has regained an appetite for buying goods on credit,
adding to signs of growing consumer confidence and encouraging hopes that
the UK economic recovery can be sustained.
Net lending to consumers increased to a seasonally adjusted Pounds 232m in
March from Pounds 54m in February, the highest since April 1991, according
to Central Statistical Office figures released yesterday.
The March figure was also more than twice City expectations that consumer
borrowing would rise by a net Pounds 90m in the month.
The CSO monthly net lending figures cover consumer borrowings from finance
houses, other specialist credit companies, building societies (excluding
mortgage lending) and on bank credit cards under the Visa and Mastercard
systems.
The amount of new credit advanced to consumers by these lenders was Pounds
4.73bn in March, the highest monthly figure since such statistics were first
published in 1987. The new credit figure compared with February's total of
Pounds 4.42bn and the Pounds 3.98bn of new consumer credit granted in March
last year.
Yesterday's statistics were welcomed in the Treasury where a spokesman said
they were consistent with other evidence of rising consumer confidence such
as retail sales, strong growth of bank notes and coins in circulation, and
opinion poll evidence of increased consumer optimism.
They coincided with official producer prices figures showing that underlying
inflationary pressures were less than expected last month.
Mr Peter Spencer, chief economist of Kleinwort Benson, the investment
banking group, said the credit figures were very significant. 'They show
that consumers are confident enough about jobs and the general economic
situation to go out and borrow again which is essential if the recovery is
to gain pace'.
In the middle of last year, consumers were net repayers of credit. The
strong March figure brought net lending to consumers by finance houses,
building societies and through the Visa and Mastercard systems to Pounds
436m in the first quarter compared with Pounds 226m in the final quarter of
last year and Pounds 142m in the first quarter of 1992.
Producer prices, Page 7
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6141 Personal Credit Institutions.
    P9611 Administration of General Economic Programs.
</IN>
<XX>
