<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 93 / EBRD directors demand spending inquiry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID HELLIER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE COMMITTEE looking into allegations of overspending at the European Bank
of Reconstruction and Development has proposed a sweeping inquiry which will
look at most aspects of the bank's spending policies, including 'special
flight arrangements'.
The committee has recommended that four international firms of auditors be
asked to tender for the role of adviser. The bank's own external auditors,
Deloitte Touche and Tohmatsu will not be among them.
The terms of reference drawn up at a meeting of the EBRD's board of
directors yesterday are rigorous and include what the document describes as
an 'arms length' relationship with the bank's management during the inquiry
given the sensitivity of its work. This, says the document, requires '
strict adherence to confidentiality and independence.'
Mr Claes de Neergaard, Chairman of the Audit Committee, which includes EBRD
directors, has proposed that, in addition to external auditors, outside
quantity surveyors and architects should be appointed 'to ensure the
appearance of absolute independence and objectivity'.
The committee, which will meet in closed session, has asked for between
Pounds 200,000-300,000 to carry out its investigation.
It plans to deliver its report by July 15 although there is scope for it to
carry on longer.
The bank yesterday declined to comment on the audit committee's proposals
for how it wished to conduct its inquiry.
Mr Attali is also believed to have accepted that the committee should look
at the bank's use of private jets.
The inquiry was set up after widespread calls from the bank's international
shareholders following revelations in the Financial Times of expenditure of
Pounds 55.5m by the bank on its London headquarters.
The committee's remit on the EBRD's headquarters expenses will include, but
not be limited to, a review of:
The adequacy of the procedures for tendering and procurement to ensure that
services and goods were processed and payments were made in a regular and
proper fashion so as to obtain proper value for money
*the cost effectiveness of the specification for the project as a whole
*the adequacy of the arrangements for reporting progress on the project to
the board of directors
*the adequacy of the arrangements for managing the project, both within the
bank and between the main contracting parties taking account of best
practice in the European Community
*looking at whether the bank's policy and procedures with respect to fitting
out the temporary headquarters at Leadenhall Street were justified.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>LUZ  Luxembourg, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6081 Foreign Banking and Branches and Agencies.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>MGMT  Management &amp; Marketing.
</TP>
