<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 93 / UK's late-payment culture attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UK BUSINESSES face greater delays in the payment of bills than many of their
Continental European counterparts as companies put short-term financial
advantage before contractual obligations, according to a study released
today.
The UK's record for paying bills between 15 and 60 days late is 'notably
worse' than in France, Italy, Belgium or the Netherlands, says the study
undertaken by Manchester Business School for National Westminster Bank.
The research underlined the problems for small businesses from late payment,
which have intensified during the recession.
Late payment, says the study, 'is a demonstration that the business culture
ranks monetary gain above ethical behaviour.'
The Federation of Small Businesses, which has 58,000 members, said last
night that late payment of bills had taken a serious toll on companies
across the country.
Mr Tony Miller, the federation's financial affairs chairman, said: 'Clients
are constantly having to chase accounts and we are now seeing companies
being paid in instalments to spread the cost. It has grown much worse during
the recession.'
The report cast doubt on the assumption that the problem of late payment is
inflicted by large companies on small suppliers. Although the finances of
small companies suffer disproportionately from late payment, they are no
better than large companies in paying bills promptly.
'Large companies may well be late payers, but small and medium-sized
enterprises are at least as bad and probably worse,' the report says.
The study supported a proposal, which has been backed by the Forum of
Private Business, a small business lobby group, for legislation to give
companies a statutory right to interest on unpaid bills.
It also called for a reduction in credit periods, which it said would
improve the cashflow of many UK companies. It said that small manufacturers
and wholesalers would gain from shorter credit periods. Payment Practices,
Legislation and their effect on SMEs: A Comparative Study, available from
National Westminster Bank, Small Business Services, Fenchurch Exchange, 8
Fenchurch Street, London EC3M 4PB. Price Pounds 25
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
