<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 93 / Tec chiefs call for wider action: The partnership between
the employer-led Training and Enterprise Councils and the government is one
of the most ambitious forged with the private sector. The performance of the
Tecs, which handle Pounds 2.3bn of public money each year, will help
determine the private sector's willingness to push ahead with other
programmes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHITEHALL should better co-ordinate its activities in training and
education, say directors of the 82 Tecs in England and Wales.
The finding is one of several in the FT's survey which questioned the
working relationships within the government and those between Whitehall and
Tecs. These are the bodies contract with a number of government departments,
including education, employment and trade and industry, to provide training
and enterprise activities.
One third of directors want a much more fundamental co-ordination of
ministerial responsibilities, suggesting that Tecs should emulate Scotland
where their equivalents, Local Economic Councils (Lecs), have strong parent
bodies - Scottish Enterprise and the Highlands and Islands Enterprise. These
statutory bodies fund the Lecs and devolve activities to them - not only
training, but also the economic development powers of the Scottish
Development Agency.
Going down this route would require radical reform in Whitehall, to include
concentrating regional aid under one wing.
A recurring theme is the need for a stronger focus by departments on
activities that involve Tecs. One businessman says: 'Far too little has been
done to unite all the diverse bodies involved in, say, tackling
unemployment. The operation is fragmented beyond belief. At the government
level there are three departments all coming at the problem from different
angles and at the local level there are county councils, district councils,
the Employment Service and Tecs, all with different priorities.'
When it comes to their own priorities, directors are forthright. Sixty three
per per cent rate economic development as their priority, including job
creation. Only 17 per cent say training the unemployed is their top
priority.
A total of 68 per cent of directors believe the amount of money the
government spends on training via the Tecs is too low, while only 2 per cent
say it is too high.
Many are still pessimistic about the government's approach to promoting the
training of those in work. Forty nine per cent of directors generally - and
39 per cent of executives - advocate a statutory training levy, rather than
leaving it up to the company.
Just under half - 46 six per cent - back Workfare, one of the most
controversial proposals, which would force specific groups of the unemployed
to work or undertake training in return for benefits.
On the whole, the directors are generally enthusiastic over government
initiatives - more than 80 per cent welcome the pilots for a scheme under
which employers are given a subsidy to take on someone who has been without
work for a long time. One director says: 'This scheme should be extended
nationwide. It just may give companies that extra bit of confidence to
employ another person that they could not really afford.'
FT 1993 Survey of Tecs. Marketing Department, Financial Times, 1 Southwark
Bridge, London SE1 9HL. Pounds 5.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
