<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 93 / Directors devote effort by the hour: The partnership between
the employer-led Training and Enterprise Councils and the government is one
of the most ambitious forged with the private sector. The performance of the
Tecs, which handle Pounds 2.3bn of public money each year, will help
determine the private sector's willingness to push ahead with other
programmes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BEING an unpaid director of one of the 82 Training and Enterprise Councils
in England and Wales is a time-consuming activity.
A total of 56 per cent of the 506 respondents to the survey of 1,220 Tec
directors said they spent more than three hours a week on Tec-related
activities. Twenty eight per cent of those said the Tec took more than six
hours a week - an increase from 16 per cent last year.
The recession has caused many directors, particularly from the private
sector - who have to be of chief-executive status - to question their
commitment to outside activities. But only one said he was leaving his Tec
because of the time factor.
And 91 per cent said they intended to spend more than two years with their
Tec - only 45 per cent expressed such a committment last year.
Representatives of trade unions, who made up nearly 5 per cent of the
survey, were as prepared to stay the course as the private-sector
executives, who accounted for 68 per cent of respondents. The remainder were
public-sector officers.
Most found the overall progress of Tecs to be satisfactory but only 17 per
cent were very satisfied compared with 26 per cent last year. Ten per cent
said progress was very unsatisfactory compared with 7 per cent last year.
Union and public-sector representatives were the most critical.
</TEXT>
