<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 93 / FT Training and Enterprise Council Survey:  The partnership
between the employer-led Training and Enterprise Councils and the government
is one of the most ambitious forged with the private sector. The performance
of the Tecs, which handle Pounds 2.3bn of public money each year, will help
determine the private sector's willingness to push ahead with other
programmes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Questionnaires were sent to 1,220 Tec directors.  The majority of these were
senior businessmen and women from the private sector.  A minority came from
the public sector and trade unions.  A total of 506 replies were received
and the main findings were:
More than 88 per cent of directors have been with their Tec for more than
one year
90 per cent expect to spend more than two years with the Tec
28 per cent spend more than six hours a week on Tec-related activities
72 per cent are satisfied with Tecs' progress generally, the greatest level
of dissatisfaction being expressed by members of trade unions
78 per cent believe Tecs should be the subject of minor evolutionary reform.
 Trade union members are again the most critical with 37 per cent alling for
drastic reform
68 per cent believe the government's spending on training via Tecs is too
low
49 per cent believe there should be a levy on business to pay for training
people in work.  Nearly 40 per cent of business executives share this view
A majority are unhappy with the current intermediary body between Tecs and
government - called G10 and made up of 10 Tec chairmen.  30 per cent of
critics of G10 want a stronger intermediary body, along the lines of
Scottish Enterprise, which funds the Scottish equivalent of Tecs
Youth Training, the government-funded scheme for 16-19 year olds, is seen as
important or very important by 96 per cent of directors
78 per cent favour a 'universal credit' which would entitle all 16-19 year
olds to full and part-time education and training
51 per cent say a department of education and training should be created
43 per cent believe the government's new Training for Work scheme for the
adult jobless, with its emphasis on payment for getting people into jobs or
gaining qualifications, could force Tecs to discriminate against individuals
who need a lot of help
30 per cent say the relationship between their Tec and the local careers
services is unsatisfactory
90 per cent say their Tecs relationship with schools is either very good or
good
51 per cent are satisfied with the progress of Investors in People - the
scheme to improve training of people in work - in their areas.  33 say they
are dissatisfied
70 per cent of directors' own companies or, in the case of trade union
members and local authority representatives, are committed to being awarded
IIP.
54 per cent believe the promotion of Inward Investment into their area is
inadequate
56 per cent are in favour of some form of workfare targeted at specific
groups
</TEXT>
