<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 93 / Vulnerable Lamont dogged by Tory calls for his departure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR NORMAN Lamont will this week try to shrug off mounting criticism of his
economic stewardship - but he faces an insurmountable task in squashing
speculation of his removal in a summer reshuffle.
Ministers yesterday acknowledged that the chancellor had become a lightning
conductor for Tory MPs' alarm over the whole government's performance and
argued that personal criticism of him was unfair.
But Downing Street and cabinet ministers have done little to counter
suggestions that Mr John Major will reshuffle his cabinet around the summer
recess at the end of July.
With Mr Lamont's reputation already damaged following Britain's traumatic
exit from the European exchange rate mechanism, there is now a widespread
belief at Westminster that he is too great a liability to be saved. He may,
however, be offered the dignity of another senior cabinet post.
No cabinet minister has speculated publicly on how long Mr Lamont will
remain at the Treasury, but the number of senior Tories who are privately
urging his removal is growing.
In a speech to the Scottish Tory party conference on Wednesday Mr Lamont
will attempt to rebuild confidence that the government's economic policies
will lead to sustainable economic growth.
Yet the audience's reaction may show the depth of Mr Lamont's unpopularity
among Tory activists - even though criticism after Thursday's election
results is strongest in the traditional Conservative heartlands of southern
England.
Among grassroots Tories there is contempt at Mr Lamont's ability to dismiss
the volte face over the ERM without appreciating the recession's impact on
individual lives. There is a perception too that Mr Major tried for too long
last year to save Mr David Mellor as national heritage secretary and that
the same mistake should not be repeated.
Mr Lamont's 'je ne regrette rien' remark during the Newbury by-election was
seen as insensitive, smacking of arrogance where contrition would have
fitted better.
In the short term Mr Lamont is probably safe. He himself argues that the
prime minister cannot be bounced into decisions by press hounding. In
comments which, perhaps deliberately fell short of fulsome backing, Mr
Kenneth Clarke, home secretary and a possible successor as chancellor, said
yesterday: 'It is the unfairness of the treatment of Norman that has caused
his colleagues to rally to him in recent months.'
Mr Michael Portillo, chief secretary to the Treasury, and tipped as another
possibility for the chancellorship, said on BBC television that the
chancellor had been the victim of a 'virulent press campaign'.
To an extent they are right that the treatment of Mr Lamont is too
personalised. To some Tory MPs he is a scapegoat - to blame Mr Lamont is
easier than voicing fears that the problems facing the government under Mr
Major go far wider.
But the vicissitudes of politics mean scapegoats are inevitable when a party
is in trouble. Mr Lamont, who was appointed chancellor when Mrs Margaret
Thatcher was toppled as prime minister, would not be the first to complain
at the injustices of politics.
</TEXT>
