<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 93 / Treasury considers trying out a newer model: Peter Marsh on
moves to update software for economic forecasting
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AFTER London Zoo and the Royal Family another well-loved British institution
is under threat. The Treasury model - a set of computer programs depicting
how the UK economy works - could be replaced by rival software under one
option being considered by government officials.
The demise of the 20-year-old model would have a big effect on how the
Treasury prepares its economic forecasts.
The Treasury model has entered the spotlight partly because of the
inadequacies of the Treasury's recent forecasts, which in common with many
private-sector projections failed to spot either the 1986-88 boom or the
seriousness of the recession before it was too late.
Although the model can hardly take the full blame for the poor predictions -
other important factors include the judgments made by Treasury economists
and the political 'spin' imparted to projections by ministers - Treasury
officials concede the software in the model has not been kept sufficiently
up to date.
They have asked academic experts from Strathclyde University and Warwick
University to improve aspects of the model concerned with labour markets and
consumer spending.
In the US the job of preparing economics forecasts on behalf of President
Bill Clinton's administration is shared by the so-called 'economics troika'
 -the US Treasury, the Office of Management and Budget and the Council of
Economic Advisers. All use private-sector models.
A senior administration official said: 'Contracting out modelling gives us
greater flexibility. It also improves our credibility because people know we
are using independent economic analysis.'
Mr Bob Dennis, assistant economics director at the Congressional Budget
Office, said: 'By piggybacking on work done outside the government we get
the best of whatever expertise is available.'
Massachusetts-based DRI, the world's biggest economics consultancy with
annual sales of about Dollars 60m (Pounds 38.90), and McKibbin Software
Group, a small modelling company in Washington DC, are among several US
groups which supply models to the US agencies. DRI charges about Dollars
20,000 a year for its software, including help in forecasts and monthly
updating of the computer code to allow for economic fluctuations.
DRI and McKibbin have indicated interest in supplying the UK Treasury with
their own versions of modelling software for the UK economy. DRI economists
outlined their thinking to the Treasury at a meeting in January.
From the UK, Business Strategies, a small London-based economics
consultancy, would 'definitely be interested' in selling the UK Treasury
modelling software, according to Mr Charles Burton, joint managing director.
The Treasury is also evaluating UK models run by the London Business School
and the National Institute of Economic and Social Research as candidates for
internal use, possibly in conjunction with the existing Treasury model.
Mr Warwick McKibbin, founder of McKibbon Software Group, thinks that
whatever the result of the review at the UK Treasury, it should buy other
models to use alongside its own. 'Anyone interested in the economy should
have access to two or three models because they all have their own strengths
and weaknesses,' he said.
The Treasury model, which runs on desk-top computers, is used to simulate
how a set of policy actions such as changes in interest rates affect
variables such as consumer spending or jobs vacancies.
It comprises more than 100 mathematical equations linking variables such as
unemployment, inflation and budget deficits.
It is tended by a team of 30 Treasury economists. They are answerable to Mr
Alan Budd, who is the department's chief economic adviser.
Dozens, if not hundreds, of models are used worldwide to simulate activities
in specific economies. They differ from each other largely in the way their
equations link up variables and how easy they are to use.
Any decision to scrap the Treasury model and rely entirely on the private
sector would come after the Treasury finishes its modelling review at the
end of the summer.
Mr John Watts, the Tory MP who is chairman of the Commons' Treasury and
Civil Service committee, supports the use of a greater range of models.
Referring to the Treasury's recently-appointed committee of outside economic
advisers, Mr Watts said: 'There would be an advantage to the Treasury having
more than one model. It's already got seven wise men, so why not seven wise
models?'
It could also open the door to a number of companies in the US and UK which
would like to sell their own economic models to the Treasury.
</TEXT>
