<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 93 / Pay rises 'below 3% for first time in 9 years'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AVERAGE PAY increases have dropped below 3 per cent for the first time in
nine years, with a quarter of settlements in the first three months of the
year worth 1.8 per cent or less, according to figures released today by
Industrial Relations Services, the independent pay research company.
It says in a report that the number of pay freezes has yet to peak, with one
in five employers among the latest batch to settle giving their workers no
increase or deferring rises.
In the three months to the end of March, settlements covering nearly 1m
employees dipped to 2.9 per cent, compared with 4.5 per cent a year ago.
This is the first time that the 3 per cent barrier has been breached since
IRS pay databank figures on about 1,000 bargaining groups became available
nine years ago.
IRS predicts that when public-sector pay deals, backdated to April, are
eventually included the level of increases will be pushed down even further.
Most public-sector staff covered by pay review bodies will receive 1.5 per
cent rises in line with the government's ceiling on public-sector pay.
IRS says that the only public-sector group likely to put up any real
resistance to the 1.5 per cent limit is the firefighters.
Their increase is not due until November but the Fire Brigades Union has
made clear that there is a risk of industrial action if local authority
employers do not honour a pay formula which links firefighters' earnings to
the top quarter of average male manual earnings.
The union's annual conference in Bridlington, Humberside, this week is
likely to discuss a strike ballot.
In the National Health Service pay negotiations which should have been
concluded in April are progressing slowly with different groups of workers
involved in what IRS calls a 'slow bicycle race'.
IRS says NHS unions are 'anxious to avoid reaching the stage of, say,
ballotting on industrial action over the 1.5 per cent first'.
Pay and Benefits Bulletin 327, IRS, 18-20 Highbury Place, London N5 1QP.
Annual subscription Pounds 140.
</TEXT>
