FT  10 MAY 93 / Ashdown renews approach to Labour
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR PADDY Ashdown, Liberal Democrat leader, yesterday tried to step up
pressure on the Labour party and his own colleagues to work in a broader
movement for political reform in Britain.
Without 'a re-shaping of British politics,' the Liberal Democrat and Labour
parties were in danger of drifting into irrelevance, Mr Ashdown said on BBC
television.
Labour's leadership remained cool about Liberal Democrat advances, insisting
that it was Mr Ashdown who should move towards them and not visa versa.
Neither party is talking about formal pacts.
A senior Labour party official denied reports that Mr John Smith, Labour
leader, might postpone decisions on the party's links with trade unions
beyond its autumn conference, a delay that would have provoked much Liberal
Democrat criticism.
In spite of swelling opposition among trade unionists, Mr Smith is
determined to push ahead with plans for ending the trade union's involvement
in elections for the party leadership and the selection of parliamentary
candidates.
Separately Mr Tony Blair, shadow home secretary, was upbeat about
modernising the party's structure and policies. He said Labour had led the
way on democratic and constitutional reform: 'Of course if Liberal Democrat
supporters like it, that's fine,' he said.
