<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 93 / Pope denounces Mafia actions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AP
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   AGRIGENTO, SICILY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
POPE John Paul II strongly condemned Mafia bosses yesterday, saying they
face the wrath of God unless they forsake their evil ways, AP reports from
Agrigento, Sicily.
'God once said, 'Don't kill.' Man, any man, any group of men, the Mafia,
can't change and trample this most sacred law of God,' the pope said in a
voice shaking with rage.
The outburst at the end of his visit to this Mafia bastion was the Catholic
Church's strongest condemnation of organised crime. The criticism, whose
vehemence stunned observers, came in impromptu remarks at an outdoor Mass in
the Valley of Temples, beneath a hilltop cluster of 5th century BC temples,
Earlier thousands heard the Pope pay homage to law officers who have tried
to clamp down on the Mafia.
'During this latest visit in Sicily, I can't help but recall, with
particular emotion, those who, in affirming the ideals of justice and law,
paid for their commitment to the struggle against the violent forces of evil
with the sacrifice of their lives,' he told a crowd outside Agrigento's
cathedral.
Several hours later, the Pope met the parents of Judge Rosario Livatino, who
was killed outside Agrigento in 1990. The Mafia allegedly ordered the
judge's death after he refused to let the Mafia sway him in issuing a
sentence.
The murders of Mafia investigators Giovanni Falcone and Paolo Borsellino has
also fuelled anger against the Mafia across the island. 'They are martyrs of
justice, indirectly of the faith,' the pope said.
</TEXT>
