FT  08 MAY 93 / Food &amp; Drink: Appetisers
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Oddbins has followed up its successful policy of selling small lots of
cask-strength malt whiskies. The latest are a Scapa 1983, from the least
well-known of Orkney's two working distilleries (Pounds 19.99); Brora 1972,
from a now-closed distillery in the Highlands (Pounds 29.99); Springbank
1973, from Campbeltown (Pounds 29.99); and Ardbeg 1978 from Islay (Pounds
29.99). The Scapa is predictably light; the Brora exceptional; the
Springbank marred slightly by a too-obvious Bourbon cask note; and the
Ardbeg, with its peaty Islay reek, very worthy.
Oddbins, incidentally, has pulled off a considerable coup in introducing
Islay spring water (79p for 75cls) to its range. This authentically brown,
peaty Islay water provides an authentic counterpoint to your best malts.
The sherry house of Gonzalez Byass has released two sherries known
previously only on the Spanish market. These are their ManzaniIIa El Rociol
(cPounds 6.49) and their super-sweet Pedro Ximenez dessert wine Noe (cPounds
18.59). The former is a fine Manzanilla - essentially, a dry fino aged by
the sea to give it a salty tang. The 25-year-old Noe', with 450 grams of
unfermented sugar per litre, is said to be wonderful with ice cream. For
stockists, call 071-491-0623.
